canonical:
  title: 伐女眞取地築設城池實入丁戶訖獻功表
  author: 林彦
  language: lzh
  text: 臣瓘言聖上以東女眞背逆作亂將欲問罪懲惡以去年冬十一月二十四日幸御西京十二月初一日於祖眞殿前親授臣鈇鉞臣受命分兵四道而行至十三日到定州界首十四日昧爽撤去關防出軍急擊大破平定就築城池六所奏依聖旨定名訖一曰鎭東軍咸州大都督府充一千九百四十八丁戶二曰安嶺軍英州防禦使充一千二百三十八丁戶三曰寧海軍雄州防禦使充一千四百三十六丁戶四曰吉州防禦使充六百八十丁戶五曰福州防禦使充六百八十丁戶六曰公嶮鎭防禦使充五百三十二丁戶各令守禦者聖人之德允合於乾坤仁義之兵已平其夷狄惟將及卒旣懽且呼中賀 竊以潛伏奧區寔繁醜類遠從爾祖曾之世甞被我朝家之恩狼貪寢畜其叛心犬吠頻狺於外戶侵軼關塞寇攘士民狃制御之寬而謂之易凌肆覬覦之志而謂之莫禦先王故憤而欲伐陛下方繼而爲圖以兵危故始憚裁施以謀衆故終歸滯泥然而策勝負者存乎熟知變通者貴乎時事機可乘聖智獨照先休吾士卒以觀其可用繼慮彼虛實以指其必擒乃命元戎亟行大戮而臣受節鉞之制擧鉦鼓而行氣動於軍威加於敵江河注壑寸膠不能以防之碬石轉峯虛卵决然其破矣俘虜踰於半萬斬馘近於五千委積散於閭閻奔走交於道路山川險阻城池因得以高深原野膏腴田井亦從而耕鑿在昔人求而未得者今玆天與而旣取之上足以謝宗廟在天之靈下足以雪朝廷積年之恥且彼周王獫狁之伐漢帝㐫奴之征所以拓土開邊而得爲民去害比之今日宜在下風此豈微臣淺智駑材能成巨效實由陛下聖謀神筭坐定遐陬苟非其然孰使之矣伏乞命書史冊垂耀無窮臣無任瞻天賀聖激切屛營之至
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 伐女眞取地築設城池實入丁戶訖獻功表
  author: 林彦
  language: lzh
  text: 臣瓘言。聖上以東女眞背逆作亂。將欲問罪懲惡。以去年冬十一月二十四日。幸御西京。十二月初一日。於祖眞殿前。親授臣鈇鉞。臣受命分兵四道而行。至十三日。到定州界首。十四日昧爽。撤去關防。出軍急擊。大破平定。就築城池六所。奏依聖旨定名訖。一曰鎭東軍咸州大都督府。充一千九百四十八丁戶。二曰安嶺軍英州防禦使。充一千二百三十八丁戶。三曰寧海軍雄州防禦使。充一千四百三十六丁戶。四曰吉州防禦使。充六百八十丁戶。五曰福州防禦使。充六百八十丁戶。六曰公嶮鎭防禦使。充五百三十二丁戶。各令守禦者。聖人之德。允合於乾坤。仁義之兵。已平其夷狄。惟將及卒。旣懽且呼。中賀。 竊以潛伏奧區。寔繁醜類。遠從爾祖曾之世。甞被我朝家之恩。狼貪寢畜其叛心。犬吠頻狺於外戶。侵軼關塞。寇攘士民。狃制御之寬而謂之易凌。肆覬覦之志而謂之莫禦。先王故憤而欲伐。陛下方繼而爲圖。以兵危故。始憚裁施。以謀衆故。終歸滯泥。然而策勝負者存乎熟。知變通者貴乎時。事機可乘。聖智獨照。先休吾士卒。以觀其可用。繼慮彼虛實。以指其必擒。乃命元戎。亟行大戮。而臣受節鉞之制。擧鉦鼓而行。氣動於軍。威加於敵。江河注壑。寸膠不能以防之。碬石轉峯。虛卵决然其破矣。俘虜踰於半萬。斬馘近於五千。委積散於閭閻。奔走交於道路。山川險阻。城池因得以高深。原野膏腴。田井亦從而耕鑿。在昔人求而未得者。今玆天與而旣取之。上足以謝宗廟在天之靈。下足以雪朝廷積年之恥。且彼周王獫狁之伐。漢帝㐫奴之征。所以拓土開邊。而得爲民去害。比之今日。宜在下風。此豈微臣淺智駑材。能成巨效。實由陛下聖謀神筭。坐定遐陬。苟非其然。孰使之矣。伏乞命書史冊。垂耀無窮。臣無任瞻天賀聖激切屛營之至。
korean:
  title: 여진을 쳐서 그 땅을 빼앗아 성을 쌓고 못을 마련하고 실입정호를 마치고 공을 드린 표
  author: 임언
  language: kor
  text: |-
    신 윤관(尹瓘)은 아뢰옵니다.성상(聖上)께옵서 동여진(東女眞)이 배반하여 난리를 꾸미고 있으므로 죄를 묻고 악을 징계할 양으로, 지난해 겨울 11월 24일에 서경(西京)에 거동하시어, 12월 1일에 조진전(祖眞殿) 앞에서 친히 신에게 부월(鈇鉞)을 주시기에, 신은 명령을 받고 군사를 네 길로 나누어 출발한바, 13일에 정주(定州) 지경에 당도하여 14일 새벽녘에 관방(關防)을 철거하고 군사를 내어 급히 쳐서 크게 깨뜨려 평정시킨 다음에, 여섯 군데 성지(城池)를 쌓고 성지(聖旨)에 의하여 이름 정하기를 끝마쳤사옵니다.제1은 진동군(鎭東軍) 함주대도독부(咸州大都督府)니, 정호(丁戶)는 1천 9백 48로 충당시켰고, 제2는 안령군(安嶺軍) 영주방어사(英州防禦使)니, 정호는 1천 2백 28로 충당시켰고, 제3은 영해군(寧海軍) 웅주방어사(雄州防禦使)니 정호는 1천 4백 36으로 충당시켰고, 제4는 길주방어사(吉州防禦使)니, 정호는 6백 80으로 충당시켰고, 제5는 복주방어사(福州防禦使)니, 정호는 6백 80으로 충당시켰고, 제6은 공험진방어사(公嶮鎭防禦使)니, 정호는 5백 32로 충당시켜, 각각 수비 방어하게 하였사옵니다.성인(聖人)의 덕이 진실로 천지에 합하시어, 인의(仁義)의 군사가 이미 저 되놈을 평정하였사오니, 장수와 군사들이 즐거워 노래를 하옵니다. 중하(中賀)
    그윽이 생각하오면, 구석진 곳에 잠복하여 살며, 수효가 많은 그 추한 무리들이 멀찍이 제 조부ㆍ증조부의 세대로부터 우리 국가의 은혜를 입었사오나, 탐심 많은 이리떼가 차츰 그 반역의 마음을 기르고, 미친 개가 자주 바깥 문에서 짖어대어 관새(關塞)를 침략하고 사민(士民)을 약탈하며, 제어(制禦)의 너그러움을 이용하여, ‘능멸하기 쉽다.’ 이르고, ‘노려보는 뜻이 가득 차서 막아내지 못하리라.’ 이르기로, 선왕(先王)은 분히 여겨 치고자 하셨고, 폐하는 계속하여 계획을 세우셨으나, 병(兵)이란 위태로운 것이기 때문에 처음에는 거사하기를 꺼렸고, 중론이 구구하므로 마침내 교착되고 말았던 것입니다. 그러하오나 승부를 꾀하는 데는 익숙한 판단이라야 하고, 변통을 아는 자는 시기를 귀히 여기는 것이니 기회를 탈 수 있다는 것을 성지(聖智)만이 짐작하고, 먼저 우리 군사를 휴식시켜 쓸 수 있는가를 관찰하고, 저쪽의 허실(虛實)을 염탐해서 반드시 사로잡을 것을 지적하자, 이에 원융(元戎)을 명령하여 신속히 큰 토벌을 시행하였던 것입니다.신은 절월(節鉞)의 대명을 받고서 정고(鉦鼓)를 들고 떠나오매, 기운은 군사를 격동시키고 위엄은 적에게 가하여, 큰 강물이 구렁을 쏟는 듯하여 촌교(寸膠)가 막아낼 수 없었고, 돌 덩어리가 봉우리에서 구르는 듯하여 새 알이 바싹 깨지고 말았으니, 포로는 5천을 넘었고 베인 목은 5천에 가까웠으며, 쌓아놓은 곡식은 여염(閭閻)에 흩어졌고, 갈팡질팡하는 자가 길에 가득하였으며, 산천이 험준하매 성지(城池)도 높고 깊게 마련되고, 들판이 기름져서 밭도 갈고 우물도 파게 되었사온바, 옛날 사람들은 구하여도 얻지 못하던 것을 지금은 하늘이 주어서 이미 차지하게 되었으니, 위로는 종묘(宗廟)와 하늘에 계신 신령에게 사(謝)할 수 있고, 아래로는 조정의 해묵은 부끄러움을 씻을 수 있었습니다. 더구나 저 주왕(周王)이 험윤(獫狁)을 친 것과 한제(漢帝) 흉노(凶奴)를 친 것은, 토지를 넓히고 변방을 개척하여 백성을 위하여 해독을 제거하자는 것이니, 오늘날과 비교한다면 마땅히 아래 급에 있을 것입니다. 어찌 미신(微臣)의 얕은 지혜와 노둔한 자질로서 능히 큰 공을 거두었겠습니까. 실로 폐하의 성스러우신 꾀와 신기한 계산으로 앉아서 먼 지방을 평정하신 것이옵니다. 만약 그렇지 않다면 뉘가 능히 이렇게 하겠습니까. 엎드려 바라옵건대, 명령을 내려 사책(史冊)에 기록하게 하여, 무궁한 세대에 빛나게 하시옵소서. 신은 하늘을 우러러 성상께 축하하오며 격절(激切)하고 송구한 마음을 이길 길 없사옵니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0470_010_0150&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial on the Subjugation of the Eastern Jurchen, the Acquisition of Their Lands, the Construction of Fortifications and Reservoirs, the Settlement of Registered Households, and the Presentation of Achievements
  author: Yun Gwan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant Yun Gwan respectfully submits:

    Your Majesty, perceiving that the Eastern Jurchen have rebelled in treachery and lawlessness, resolved to punish their crimes and chastise their wickedness. In the eleventh month of last winter, on the twenty-fourth day, you graced the Western Capital with your presence. On the first day of the twelfth month, before the Hall of Ancestral Reverence, you yourself bestowed upon your servant the axes of command. Receiving this mandate, your servant divided the armies into four columns and marched forth. On the thirteenth day, we reached the borders of Jeongju. At dawn on the fourteenth day, we dismantled the border fortifications, deployed our forces with swift violence, and achieved a great victory, bringing peace to the region. We then constructed six fortified cities and established their names according to Your Majesty's sacred directive:

    First, the Jindongjun Military Command, the Grand Commandery of Hamju—populated with one thousand nine hundred and forty-eight registered households.

    Second, the Anryeongjun Military Command, the Defense Prefect of Yungju—populated with one thousand two hundred and thirty-eight registered households.

    Third, the Yeonghaegun Military Command, the Defense Prefect of Ungjou—populated with one thousand four hundred and thirty-six registered households.

    Fourth, the Defense Prefect of Gilju—populated with six hundred and eighty registered households.

    Fifth, the Defense Prefect of Bokju—populated with six hundred and eighty registered households.

    Sixth, the Defense Prefect of Gongheomjin—populated with five hundred and thirty-two registered households.

    We have assigned to each garrison the duty of defense. The virtue of the Sage resonates with Heaven and Earth. The righteous armies of benevolence and justice have subdued these barbarians. Officers and soldiers alike rejoice and sing in celebration.

    Humbly reflecting upon this matter: Those wretched creatures who lurk in remote recesses are numerous indeed. From the days of their ancestors and forefathers, they received the grace of our realm. Yet like wolves fattened on greed, they nursed rebellion in their hearts. Like mad dogs barking ceaselessly at the outer gates, they violated our borders and preyed upon our people. Taking advantage of our restraint, they deemed us weak. Emboldened by their ambitions, they believed we could not resist. Thus did our predecessor kings burn with indignation to strike them down, and Your Majesty continued this design. Yet because warfare is perilous, we hesitated at first to act. Because counsels were divided, we remained caught in deliberation. However, those who master victory through strategy must possess keen judgment, and those who understand change must seize the moment. Only Your Majesty's sagacious wisdom could perceive the opportunity. First allowing our soldiers rest to observe their readiness, then investigating the enemy's strengths and weaknesses to determine their certain capture, you commanded your generals to proceed with swift and decisive action.

    Your humble servant, bearing the insignia of command, lifted the signal drums and marched forth. The spirit animated our armies; our authority fell upon the enemy. As great rivers pour into ravines, no mere thread could have stemmed the flood. As stones tumble down mountainsides, the enemy's defenses crumbled like eggshells. We took captive more than five thousand souls. We severed the heads of nearly five thousand more. Stores of grain scattered throughout the villages. The enemy's remnants choked the roads in flight. The rugged mountains and valleys became our fortified strongholds. The fertile plains became fields worked and wells dug by our settlers.

    What men of old sought yet could not obtain, Heaven has now granted and we have seized. Above, we have vindicated the spirits of our ancestors in heaven. Below, we have washed away years of shame upon the court. The ancient Zhou kings who subdued the Xiongnu and the Han emperors who conquered the northern barbarians—they sought to expand territory and open new lands, to rid the people of scourges. Compared to today's achievement, they would pale in comparison.

    How could such a result spring from the shallow wisdom and dull talent of your humble servant? Truly it is Your Majesty's sagacious strategy and divine calculations that have brought distant regions into order through these campaigns. Had it been otherwise, who could accomplish such things?

    Your humble servant reverently requests that Your Majesty command this to be inscribed in the official histories, that its glory might shine through endless ages. Your servant is overwhelmed with gratitude, unable to contain the joy that fills his heart.
  footnotes:
    - Yun Gwan (1040-1115) was a renowned Goryeo general and strategist who led the campaigns against the Jurchen in the early 12th century.
    - The 'axes of command' (부월/鈇鉞) were symbolic insignia of military authority bestowed by the king.
    - The 'Hall of Ancestral Reverence' (조진전/祖眞殿) refers to an important temple or ceremonial hall, likely in the Western Capital (Seogyeong).
    - The six fortified cities mentioned represent the military administration of newly conquered Jurchen territories, with registered households indicating the population settled there.
